%h1#dog Filters

%p The colon character designates a filter. This allows you to pass an indented block of text as input to another filtering program and add the result to the output of Haml. The syntax is simply a colon followed by the name of the filter. For example:

%h3 :cdata
%p Surrounds the filtered text with CDATA tags.
%pre.code
  %code
    :escaped
      :cdata
        Rogelio Alvarado
%p is compiled to (only visible when see source code):
:cdata
      Rogelio Alvarado 
%p page source code: 
%pre.code
  %code
    :escaped
      <!--[CDATA[
        Rogelio Alvarado
      ]]-->

%h3 :coffee
%p Compiles the filtered text to Javascript using Cofeescript. You can also reference this filter as :coffeescript. This filter is implemented using Tilt.
%pre.code
  %code
    :escaped
      :coffee
        number   = 42
        opposite = true
%p is compiled to (only visible when see source code):
:coffee
  number   = 42
  opposite = true
%p page source code: 
%pre.code
  %code
    :escaped
      <script>
        (function() {
          var number, opposite;

          number = 42;
        
          opposite = true;
        
        }).call(this);
      </script>
          
%h3 :css
%p Surrounds the filtered text with &lt;style&gt;. Useful for including inline CSS. 
%pre.code
  %code
    :escaped
      :css
        body 
        {
          background-color:#d0e4fe;
        }
%p is compiled to (visible when see source code and this change current background color):
:css
  body 
  {
    background-color:#d0e4fe;